To create a basic search bar using PHP, you will need to follow these steps:

1. **HTML** for the user interface (the search box and button).
2. **JavaScript** (or jQuery) to handle the form submission.
3. **PHP** to process the search query.

First, let's start with the HTML part which includes a simple form that accepts a search query input from the user:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        /* Basic styling for the search bar */
        #search-form {
            width: 500px;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<form id="search-form" action="search.php" method="get">
    <input type="text" name="query" placeholder="Search here...">
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script> <!-- Optional, for basic form submission -->
<script>
    // Optional: Simplify the search process by preventing default form submission and using jQuery's .ajax() method
    $(document).ready(function(){
        $("#search-form").submit(function(e){
            e.preventDefault();
            var query = $("#query").val();
            $.ajax({
                type: "GET",
                url: "search.php",
                data: {query: query},
                success: function(data){
                    console.log("Search result: ", data);
                    // You would normally render the search results here
                }
            });
        });
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

Next, we'll create a simple PHP script (`search.php`) to handle the form submission and display results:

```php
<?php

// Assuming you have a database or data source with items that can be searched.
// For simplicity, let's just pretend it's an array for now.

$items = [
    ["name" => "Apple", "price" => 1.99],
    ["name" => "Banana", "price" => 0.59],
    ["name" => "Orange", "price" => 2.49],
];

$query = $_GET['query'];

if (empty($query)) {
    echo "Please enter a search query.";
} else {
    $searchResults = array_filter($items, function($item) use ($query){
        return strpos(strtolower($item["name"]), strtolower($query)) !== false;
    });

    if (!empty($searchResults)) {
        foreach ($searchResults as $result) {
            echo "Found: {$result['name']} - \$${$result['price']}\n";
        }
    } else {
        echo "No results found for \"$query\".";
    }
}

?>
```

This PHP script assumes that you are searching through an array of items, looking for a match in the `name` field. The search is case-insensitive.

**Important Note:** This example uses GET requests which could pose security risks if used to pass sensitive data. Always validate and sanitize any user input in your production code.

This basic setup should give you a starting point for creating a simple search functionality with PHP.

